We found out we were starting the slave as a batch job, since it was added originally to the same batch application as the master. The job name was a required parameter in the batch app and it had a lot of dependencies on Spring batch tools and jars, so somehow it was trying to start a batch job and since the job config does not exist, it would fail in the middle of processing and shut down all the beans and resources, causing the DB connection issue above. When we run the slave as a deamon or a regular spring boot app, it starts fine and executes the step to completion. 

To avoid doing a lot of rework and remove all the batch dependencies from the app to make it run as a regular Spring boot app, we used this code to make it run as a deamon : 

```
@SpringBootApplication
@IntegrationComponentScan
public class Application implements CommandLineRunner {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.exit(SpringApplication.exit(SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args)));
  }

  @Override
  public void run(String... args) throws Exception {
    System.out.println(&quot;Joining thread, you can press Ctrl+C to shutdown application&quot;);
    Thread.currentThread().join();
  }

}

``

